set.seed(08022003)

ts.df <- data_frame(Date = seq.Date(as.Date("2017-01-01"), by = 1, length.out = 100),
                    x = arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.999), n = 100),
                    y = 1.4 * x + rnorm(100)) 

# Now I am going to add a 10 point shift in y after the 70th observation
treatment.date = ts.df$Date[1] + 70
ts.df <- ts.df %>% 
  mutate(y = ifelse(Date >= treatment.date, y + 10, y)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(Date, y, x)  # Reorder the columns---this is important!

head(ts.df, 10)
## # A tibble: 10 x 3
##    Date           y     x
##    <date>     <dbl> <dbl>
##  1 2017-01-01  24.2  17.9
##  2 2017-01-02  25.5  18.5
##  3 2017-01-03  23.0  17.3
##  4 2017-01-04  22.1  16.4
##  5 2017-01-05  22.8  16.0

##  7 2017-01-07  18.8  14.2
##  8 2017-01-08  21.2  15.2
##  9 2017-01-09  17.4  13.4
## 10 2017-01-10  22.4  14.6
ggplot(data = ts.df, aes(y = value, x = Date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = y), colour = 'Red') + 
  geom_line(aes(y = x), colour = 'Blue')

# First we set our pre- and post- treatment dates
pre.treatment <- c(ts.df$Date[1], treatment.date - 1)
post.treatment <- c(treatment.date, ts.df$Date[100])

# Next we convert our dataframe into a time series object using the `zoo` package
ts.ts <- read.zoo(ts.df)

# Now we specify our model
ts.model <- CausalImpact(ts.ts, pre.treatment, post.treatment)
plot(ts.model)
## Warning: Removed 100 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 200 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

## Analysis report {CausalImpact}
## 
## 
## During the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 48.10. By contrast, in the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 38.10. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [36.84, 39.28]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is 10.00 with a 95% interval of [8.82, 11.26]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.
## 
## Summing up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 1.44K. By contrast, had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 1.14K. The 95% interval of this prediction is [1.11K, 1.18K].
## 
## The above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed an increase of +26%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [+23%, +30%].
## 
## This means that the positive effect observed during the intervention period is statistically significant and unlikely to be due to random fluctuations. It should be noted, however, that the question of whether this increase also bears substantive significance can only be answered by comparing the absolute effect (10.00) to the original goal of the underlying intervention.
## 
## The probability of obtaining this effect by chance is very small (Bayesian one-sided tail-area probability p = 0.001). This means the causal effect can be considered statistically significant.

library(tidyverse)

search.terms <- c('\"Start a business\"', 
                  '\"Psychology jobs\"', 
                  '\"Write a cover letter\"',
                  '\"What is a business\"')

leanimpact.trends <- gtrends(search.terms, geo = c("US"),
                             time = "2011-01-01 2011-12-31",
                             gprop = c("web"), hl = "en-US")$interest_over_time

# Now for some wrangling...
leanimpact.df <- leanimpact.trends %>%
  dplyr::select(date, hits, keyword) %>%
  mutate(keyword = gsub("\"", "", keyword)) %>% 
  mutate(date = as_date(date),
         keyword = as.factor(keyword)) %>% 
  mutate(hits = as.numeric(ifelse(hits == "<1", "0", hits)))

# Start by defining the treatment date as Sept 2011. Don't let me forget to mention why the
#  date is 4 Sept for treatment!
pre.treatment <- as.Date(c("2011-01-02", "2011-08-28"))
post.treatment <- as.Date(c("2011-09-04", "2011-12-25"))

# Now we create our time series object, but first we convert our dataframe from long to wide
leanimpact.df <- leanimpact.df %>% 
  mutate(keyword = gsub(" ", "", keyword)) %>% 
  spread(keyword, hits) %>% 
  dplyr::select(date, Startabusiness, everything())
leanimpact.ts <- read.zoo(leanimpact.df)

# And now for our model
leanimpact.model <- CausalImpact(leanimpact.ts, pre.treatment, post.treatment)
plot(leanimpact.model)
